Dragon House used to be called Zen Gourmet.
Dragon House still serves chinese food, but the best part about this place is the Seafood Hot Pot buffet.
Seafood Hot Pot is $18.99, but since this place is having its grand opening, they have a special price of $15.00 for seafood hot pot.
This place has fresh Dungeness crab, clams, mussels, beef, chicken, coagulated blood pudding, and excellent vegetables ready for you to cook.
There is also a wide variety of sauces for dipping your food into.
Inside is not the best looking, as it still looks a little old with the orange paint inside.
I took away a star because service was a little slow.
There was only one waitress serving the entire restaurant with tea, water, clearing plates, etc.
Overall, I will be back as their dungeness crab for hot pot is the best deal.

Not sure what happened to the review I posted couple of weeks ago.
Anyway, been back to this tiny hole in the wall restaurant about 5 times since (mostly for their dirt cheap lunch specials).
So I feel I have more to share about this place than my original review, which was just on the hot pot experience during their opening weekend promotion.
About the hot pot.
It is a seafood buffet Chinese hot pot style.
And you have a choice of soup bases to select from (regular, spicy and this Chinese herbal concoction).
The spicy one is pretty spicy, so keep that in mind when making your selection.
The cool part is that the pot has a partition, so you can order two soup bases.
The buffet originally was arranged in a manner that would have totally failed a health inspection (raw meat over vegetables, and other items that may not required as long of a cooking time, and just poor food storage techniques on the buffet line), but on my most recent visit (yesterday) they have make significant improvements, even though they still have some ways to go to be in the A range.
Originally the hot pot was $10 (50% off), but that promotion ended almost immediately after the restaurant opened.
Now it is $15 per person, which is still an excellent deal, but may one day be offered at the regular price of $20.
The selection of the food is pretty good.
I love the dumplings that they have, which along with the fish fillet, makes this a great deal for me.
Plus, hot pot is great during the cold months, and the restaurant is pretty packed at nights.
They also have a good selection of other vegetables (some I don't even know the English name for) and mushrooms!
The selection of condiments to customize your dipping sauce is good, and is now even better with labels telling you what the heck they are now.
The one thing I didn't like about the hot pot experience here is the hodgepodge of dishes and plates available at the buffet line.
It looks disorganized, and gives the perception that they are putting out all the plates, bowls and other dishes they can find in the restaurant.
The lunch and dinner specials start at $4.95, even though they still have the banner that states the lunch & dinner specials starting at $3.95 and is available all day (which for awhile was the best deal in town).
The portions are decent, and with the side of rice, will satisfy even the amateur competitive eaters amongst us.
My favorites in the $4.95 specials are the two pork chops entrees (one is spicy and the other one is not, but both are fried perfectly and served piping hot and still juicy inside).
The walnut prawns is excellent and a great value.
Service is friendly, but could be slow or inadequate on a busy dinner rush, since I see only one waitress working on all my visits to the restaurant.
The friends I brought to this restaurant all have positive impression about the restaurant, in spite of the noticeable flaws or areas of improvement that we can all clearly observed.
And the fact that I know and can see the steady improvements in the way they set up the buffet and serve great tasty food, encourages me to come back time and again when I am in the area.
Decor: 3/5 It is a hole in the wall, but at least they try to put up classical Chinese paintings to contribute to the theme.
Service: 3.5/5 It is hard to be the cashier/waitress/busser and do all of it solo most of the time.
Price/Value: 4.5/5  $4.95 + tax gets you a lot of quality Chinese food.
$15 is reasonable for a seafood hot pot buffet.
Location: 3/5  Not in the best part of town, and definitely not in the best lot in that part of town.
But sometimes you have to live dangerously to get yummy Chinese food at a low price.
Good for group???
As long as the group is not too large, since I don't see any lazy susans on the table (if you intend to order and share the entrees family style).
For hot pot it is ideal for up to 4 or 5 per hot pot, but it is not difficult to have two set up at a table for larger groups.

We had been wanting to try out this place since it first opened up about a month ago.
Price for their AYCE Chinese fondue was $10 a person when the restaurant first opened up.
This special only lasted a few days.
Now their special is 20% off of the $18.99 price per person.
So for $15 you get AYCE fondue with lots of items to select from.
We had beef, lamb, squid, shrimp, kidney, fish balls, wonton, a couple of other kind of dumplings, and crab.
They also had a variety of other organs that we did not try out.
We also had loads of spinach, watercress and napa cabbage.
The vegetables absorb the broth's flavour when boiled after the other meats are cooked.
The raw crab was brought to our table and was not on the AYCE table of items that you help yourself to.
It was so fresh and sweet.
Actually all the ingredients were very fresh and there were quite the selection of dipping sauces that were very savory.
Top marks for their wonton and shrimp dumplings, they were absolutely delicious.
I would come back just to have this if nothing else.
When it's freezing outside, go try out their AYCE fondue (hot pot), it's sure to keep you warm and fulfilled.
Will definitely go back again!
I took one star off because of their orange colour wall paper decoration and no pork and chicken on the buffet line.

I have been here a lot recently to pick up items I ordered off of their lunch special menus, which ends at 4pm, in spite of the banner hanging outside stating that they have specials all day.
Anyway, I feel that their food is good overall, and at lunch special pricing ($4.95 or $5.95) is great on the wallet and your tummy.
Unlike some other restaurants that take their time to prepare your order, the cooks working in the back is super fast making your lunch.
On my most recent visit just last week at about 2pm, my two orders were prepared, boxed and brought out in under 4 minutes.
It was so hot that I burnt my tongue eating a little of it in the car, before I set off to my appointment.
Their crab entrees also look really good, and the size of the crabs they serve is pretty big.
You can see the crabs in the tank with the lobsters.
Anyway, I would be here even more often if it was closer.
